review: So, a few weeks ago I went to a Women's Leadership Conference and it was pretty rad. At one point, they took audience questions and someone wanted to So, a few weeks ago I went to a Women's Leadership Conference and it was pretty rad. At one point, they took audience questions and someone wanted to know what books the panel read. I got excited for a minute, then I realized they meant like business or personal development books.But one of the women recommended this book and I decided to reserve it at the library because the lady who suggested it was awesome. Granted, she meant the original book probably and what I picked out and reserved on my library's tiny and not particularly mobile-friendly website was this. This is by the same author and is a cash grab supplement to the original book full of exercises and brief readings to help you stay on course. Look, I am not here to knock you down or dissuade you. But if you want this book, maybe check it out first. The advice is pretty basic: practice deep breathing, spend some time distancing your emotions from bad events, and don't forget to stretch. [image]Reader, you ARE a bad ass. And you probably already know this stuff....more

title: Reliquary        (Pendergast, #2)
author: Preston, Douglas*
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: Back in 1997, there was this pretty decent monster horror movie called Relic. It's kind of hard to find gifs of and, more germane, my s these daBack in 1997, there was this pretty decent monster horror movie called Relic. It's kind of hard to find gifs of and, more germane, my s these days get less action than the Tastee Freez in my hometown (and that place has been closed for 30 years, babump-tsssss) so, it's not really worth spelunking the Internet for. Anyway, that movie is based off of the first book and (a small) part of the second book in this series. A lot of stuff was changed but what I find most curious is the character, FBI agent Pendergast, who is the mc that runs through this long series was written out completely. Several of the other characters such as young biologist Margo Green, Chicago (NYC in the book) cop Vincent D'Agosta, elderly faculty advisor Professor Frock, and conniving competing biologist Greg Kawakita remain, in slighty altered forms. (Honestly, the Pendergast character is mad entertaining but strains credulity frequently. My favorite oddball fact: he owns an apartment in the Dakota. THE Dakota. And he works for the FBI. Okurr.) This book picks up around a year and a half after the first book. Our main characters (minus Greg, who seems to have disappeared) are trying to move on with their careers and their bad dreams when a police diver discovers two skeletons. One of them turns out to be the remains of a missing socialite and one turns out to be not exactly human so Lieutenant D'Agosta finds himself needing the expertise of the Museum of Natural History and the fabulous Dr. Margo Green again. Why does this thing look so similar to the museum monster they killed 18 months ago? Is it related to murders of homeless living in the tunnels beneath the city? WTF is track rabbit? (Y'all don't want to know and you probably really want to skip over the brief section where it's eaten.) This is high quality popcorn reading. Monsters, monster nom noms, science facts, crazy information about the multi-storied tunnels beneath Manhattan that is at least partly true, valiant cops and their incompetent leaders, conniving journalists, mean rich ladies. Lots of savory and sweet ingredients here, mixed well. I read the first book 20 years ago, so I don't remember it well. I definitely want to continue with this series though for at least a few more books. Fun trivia: co-author Douglas Preston is the brother of Richard Preston, author of The Hot Zone: The Terrifying True Story of the Origins of the Ebola Virus, amongst other things....more

title: It Waits in the Woods
author: Malerman, Josh*
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: Was this grief's only gift? The eradication of the highs, by way of leveling the lows?This is part of a collection of Amazon original stories called "Was this grief's only gift? The eradication of the highs, by way of leveling the lows?This is part of a collection of Amazon original stories called "Creature Feature", and has some pretty big modern horror names attached: Malerman, Paul Tremblay, Joe Hill, Grady Hendrix. The Original Stories series is, at least for now and hopefully going forward, available for free for Kindle Unlimited readers and this particular collection includes the audio versions for free as well. I don't seem to be able to focus well on audio for an entire book, but I'd love to hear this short story performed. Brenda and Amanda are precocious Michigan teenagers. Brenda makes movies, Amanda stars in them. Their lives are pretty promising and groovy until Amanda disappears in the woods one night. But while participating in the search party, Brenda hears the other searchers whisper to one another about a local campfire legend. About a magical bridge and a face-stealing imp named Opso. Brenda can't get this Opso guy out of her head and is convinced--in an army of one sort of way--he's responsible for Amanda's disappearance. And this is a horror story after all. Moreover, it's a horror story with fairy tale DNA. Maybe he is? [image]In unrelated news, I miss Adventure TimeI was into the story for 3/4 of the way. I can't quite decide on the ending but I'm not mad, I guess. I think maybe I'm rating it too high but I also think Malerman's writing on this is absolutely baller: the story has a chilly, goosefleshy vibe right from the jump. I can also vouch that Malerman's novel Bird Box (not the movie, don't watch the stupid movie) will leave you freaked out for a long time....more

review: I don't remember purchasing this, but Amazon tells me I did last month. Likely I was speed perusing Kindle deals, saw the name Cheryl Strayed, and immI don't remember purchasing this, but Amazon tells me I did last month. Likely I was speed perusing Kindle deals, saw the name Cheryl Strayed, and immediately clicked yes without knowing what it was. While it seems to be a bit polarizing amongst readers and I suspect Cheryl and I have either nothing or the most profound things in common, I absolutely loved and adored Wild: From Lost to Found on the Pacific Crest Trail beyond all reason. This is a very short, article length memoir (memoirticle?) about Cheryl's mother-in-law passing away but, by nature of the author, becomes a reflection on how all of us deal with family (genetic and found), the difficult relationships found within, and how we face death. It was simultaneously soothing and intense. "Thank you," she whispered with more force and clarity than I thought she had left. In three days, she'd take her last breath as Brian held her. "Thank you," she said again, like she wanted me to remember it.And I did....more

title: Ramona Quimby, Age 8        (Ramona Quimby #6)
author: Cleary, Beverly
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: Ramona decided that she preferred Sustained Silent Reading to DEAR because it sounded more grown-up. When time came for everyone to Drop Everything AnRamona decided that she preferred Sustained Silent Reading to DEAR because it sounded more grown-up. When time came for everyone to Drop Everything And Read, she sat quietly doing her Sustained Silent Reading.Oh, Ramona. Such a bright, anxious, adorably pretentious*, boisterous and, as she would surely tell us, grievously misunderstood child. Part of her appeal is that she reminds some of us adults of younger versions of ourselves. *I say "pretentious" with nothing but love, Ramona. I'm positive I would have preferred Sustained Silent Reading too. It's book #6 in the series. Ramona is in third grade and has--oh no!--another teacher she doesn't vibe with. She and her older sister Beezus are even sort of friends and allies these days some of the time, but Beezus is now far away in the junior high school. Most importantly though, her father is going back to college and the financial strain this puts on the family--who are mostly living on their mother's income as a doctor's receptionist--and the time lost with the parent who gets Ramona best will be recurring themes throughout the story. As usual, the lightness and humor are mixed with plenty of real world issues delivered in Cleary's empathetic way. Ramona overhears her new teacher saying some not too complimentary things about her which puts her in a bit of a tailspin and her parents, who have problems of their own, brush off it off as Ramona being Ramona. Additionally, Ramona and Beezus must now go to Mrs. Kemp's house after school since their parents aren't home in the afternoons. And I'm 100% Team Ramona on this one: Mrs. Kemp kind of sucks. As always, there are some hysterical scenes included, like Ramona's oral book report and Beezus and Ramona struggling to cook dinner as punishment for complaining. About dinner the night before, naturally. This book is probably the most serious in the series thus far but it's still pitch perfect in that Beverly Cleary sweet but realistic way. "That man paying for our dinner was sort of like a happy ending," remarked Beezus as the family, snug in their car, drove through the rain and the dark toward Klickitat Street. "A happy ending for today," corrected Ramona. Tomorrow they would begin all over again....more

review: A spike of alarm hits her. This is what a secret means. Everything Doug says will have two sides because he doesn't know what she did, and everything A spike of alarm hits her. This is what a secret means. Everything Doug says will have two sides because he doesn't know what she did, and everything she says will have to hide what she knows. She has to be smarter than she was. She has to be careful, and it can't show.In a future so close to our own it might as well be now, the Stella/Handy company manufactures lifelike robot companions. Do you want a nanny, or a manny? A 50's housewife who cleans and bakes? Or perhaps you'd like a Cuddle Bunny? You can probably guess what that is for. Annie Bot, or just Annie, is #3 and she's owned by a manchild named Doug, who you will almost certainly want to punch almost on sight. Annie is in autodidact mode, so she's smart, very smart, and getting smarter. Doug naturally thinks Annie's advanced perceptiveness is a reflection on him but when a duplicitous friend of his pays a surprise visit, that will set events in motion that will have profound impacts on Annie (And Doug too, but seriously, fuck that guy.) This was good, I would say not great because the ending was a bit unsatisfying. More specifically, (view spoiler)[look Doug did kind of redeem himself at the end but I was still of course 100% team Annie and I get she had nowhere else to go but she barely knows that Cody guy. They interacted in total for maybe an hour a year ago and for half of that hour, he wasn't that nice to her. It felt very abrupt and not at all certain to me he'd help her or give her a place to stay. (hide spoiler)]There was a lot to think about here about the lives of women and AI (and the last bit is something we'll have to worry about all too soon and humanity will almost definitely do a shit job of managing it I'm sure. )This was a short book and I felt like maybe because of that some threads didn't get a chance to breathe and be explored (view spoiler)[Delta Bot deserved better, sniff, and the Kenny Bot thing seems like a missed opportunity (hide spoiler)] and the ending felt rushed.I do think Sierra Greer did a good job of writing Annie's POV and subtly shifting it as Annie grew into her own. I did like this, I just didn't fall in love with it. (I might be in love with Delta Bot though...) But if you are interested, I definitely do recommend reading it....more

title: The Manicurist's Daughter
author: Lieu, Susan*
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: Even though we were boat people who came to America in 1983, Ma's awful death made us refugees a second time in 1996. We had to rebuilt our lives all Even though we were boat people who came to America in 1983, Ma's awful death made us refugees a second time in 1996. We had to rebuilt our lives all over again, but instead of doing it together as we had always done with Ma at the helm, each of us did it alone in silence. I have tried to process her death with therapists over the years, but retelling the narrative over and over again wears down even the steadiest of treadmills.Full disclosure: I won a copy of this from Celadon Books in a giveaway, so thanks to them and the author.Second disclosure, I had mixed feelings about winning this book because while I was interested in it, it also sounded like a huge bummer. Maybe you have read the description and think so too so let me say up front---Susan Lieu can WRITE, y'all. She writes like someone born to write and to be able to find your purpose like that is a blessing. When Susan Lieu was 11, her mother died from a botched tummy tuck and the surgeon, who preyed on immigrant women, never faced any real consequences. Her memoir spirals back and forth in time from this event, which was a smoking before/after crater in her life: remembering how her parents escaped to the US from Vietnam and her mother's creation of a small nail salon business from nothing that was able to provide emigration opportunities and jobs to various family members. In the aftermath, Lieu attempts to move on but can't heal from this event, particularly when her family stops talking about her mother. I find it really difficult to  memoirs since it's just someone talking about their life but this reminds me a bit of Wild: From Lost to Found on the Pacific Crest Trail. Not so much Strayed's style, for those who didn't like that book (although I loved it), but the way Lieu, like Strayed, can make any story edge-of-your-seat fascinating. The sensory overload of her stories about the food were my favorite, whether it is at the family dinner table or Sizzler. Despite the heavy subject matter, this is mesmerizing (the story of how her parents escaped from Vietnam, I mean, Jesus!) I recommend it....more

title: Big Swiss
author: Beagin, Jen
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: It was her eleventh day without a cigarette, her eleventh month without sex. She'd been smoking her feelings since she was fifteen, and now, at age thIt was her eleventh day without a cigarette, her eleventh month without sex. She'd been smoking her feelings since she was fifteen, and now, at age thirty-three her real self was beginning to emerge. Unfortunately, her real self was horny, easily enraged, and no longer interested in making money.When I first read about this book, it was an easy "Naw, I'm good" for me and it really shouldn't work: Greta gets a job transcribing sessions for a sex therapist in the small hipster hamlet of Hudson, NY, (not coincidentally where the author is from) and becomes obsessed with a married female client she refers to as "Big Swiss." One day, Greta randomly meets her at the dog park, immediately recognizes her voice, and a torrid yet highly idiosyncratic affair ensues. Big Swiss has no idea meanwhile that Greta has heard her therapy sessions. Actually, she has no idea what Greta's real name is. This book should not work but somehow it does beautifully. It's absurd and smart and melancholy and hysterically funny and delightful and I absolutely loved it. But before we get too far, serious tw's for SA and suicidal ideation. But if these topics are not “no way/no how” for you, read on. Also, my eternal, primary concern: does the dog get hurt? (view spoiler)[There are various animals in this story, but principally dogs. One does get injured and it looks like something awful might happen, but it's ok. The doggo will be ok. (hide spoiler)]Greta....felt incapable of making plans for the weekend, let alone a wedding, let alone the rest of her life, and so their engagement had lasted ten years. In the meantime, she kept catching the bouquet at other people's weddings. The bouquet was never tossed into the air, it seemed to Greta, but rather hurled directly at her head, and she had no choice but to catch it and then quickly pass it like a football to the woman standing next to her, who always dropped it. "Fumble!" Greta yelled each time. The woman would then pick up the bouquet and pass it back to Greta, and Greta would feel like dying.Greta is a very specific type of person: a hyper-articulate, overly smart, underly employed woman whose wry, casual to somewhat affectless exterior masks a boiling caldera of long bound and gagged emotions. As you read the book, more and more of how she is begins to make sense and although I wanted to shake her many times, I loved her dearly.And I haven't even told you yet the sex therapist--not a licensed psychologist, more of a well-meaning, good vibes sort--is named Om and fond of giving his patients a gong bath (which Greta originally transcribes as "dong bath", one of many moments that made me snortchoke.) The combination of colors--the bright orange with the turquoise blue of the lake, his white shirt and teeth--opened a door in Greta's mind, a door she usually preferred to keep shut and locked, but now she let herself cross the threshold and roam around. It’s not so bad in here, she thought. Maybe she'd spend more time in this room from now on. "What room?" Om said. "The future," Greta said.Beneath it all is a story about people who are hurting because the world has at some point socked them hard in the face and how they careen around and damage others, but mostly, and repeatedly, themselves. And the book is so brilliantly, meticulously put together, so meticulous that I didn't really notice until I was almost done when an anecdote that Greta casually mentions in the beginning turns out to be a moment in a much bigger, pivotal story. I had to immediately go back and read a bunch of scenes over. You are good, Jen Beagin, you sly, funny fox....more

review: He pauses. "Maybe I'll come and find you after they're settled. We can go away together like we talked about."It was not so long ago that they made thHe pauses. "Maybe I'll come and find you after they're settled. We can go away together like we talked about."It was not so long ago that they made that pact, to start over together someplace new. "The people who said that," she whispers, "were from another world. Now there is only this one."The final book in the Fennbirn quadrilogy and while it's not perfect, I have five stars worth of feels, easily. Everything is ended with perfect messy neatness though. I will miss this wacky island and this even wackier generation of triplet queens so, so much. It's giving faint Dune vibes, especially with the themes of corruption, plotting, faith, and power, and how they tie into the inevitable end of all human-made institutions. This is still YA though, so you won't be subjected to Dune-esque multi-page soliloquys. If you've made it past the second novel in the Dune series (and I have), you can't be too sorry about that. One other thing I want to praise this series for is being a YA fantasy with a minimum of romance and what a rare and beautiful unicorn that makes it. What romantic entanglements do occur here drive the plot forward in a multitude of interesting ways and are not really the focal point. No love triangle. No meet cute but with halberds. No insta-love (maybe with Emilia. Fucking Emilia, I'll get to her...) No ACOTAR bone-a-thon vibes. This is high octane, high stakes, twists and turns, tears, laughs, pins and needles, burn the midnight oil finishing the last half. This series is fucking everything, fight me.I need to talk about some things, so fetch me an elemental to summon a spoiler tag:(view spoiler)[Ahh, that's better. It crushed me when Mirabella died, although I suspected that would happen. And it crushed me (to be sure, less) when Katharine died, although she died an absolutely baller hero and definitely got the shaft in life and undeath. And Arsinoe, thought giftless for so long and weak, saves the day with low magic of all things. I still intensely dislike Emilia, but hey--I used to hate her. Still, she's pushy and very possessive/fangirly regarding Jules and I just can't get behind those qualities as a romantic partner. I don't know wtf Kendare Blake was thinking with this character. Oh well, at least Mathilde survived.I kind of loved the redemption arc, such as it was, for Pietyr Renard too. title: Rock & Roll Nightmares: True Stories, Volume 1: Fascinating Facts & Disturbing Details About Famous Rock Stars
author: Wilson, Staci Layne*
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: Staci Layne Wilson, daughter of Don Wilson, the guitarist of The Ventures, wrote this collection of vignettes about how rock stars from infamous to soStaci Layne Wilson, daughter of Don Wilson, the guitarist of The Ventures, wrote this collection of vignettes about how rock stars from infamous to somewhat obscure died. Although the chapters felt like laundry lists at times ("This person died in a plane crash, half of this band died in a plane crash, also this person died in a plane" got to be the vibe after a while), there's a lot of information here. But, while it looks like Wilson did a LOT of research (check out her bibliography), I did catch little bits and pieces that made me wonder how many other errata exist. For example:Page 112, "the Purple One and his guitarist Dr. Fink (aka, Dez Dickerson)": Heavens to Paisley Park! Dez Dickerson was a guitarist in The Revolution until he quit after the 1999 tour. Dr. Fink, on the other hand, was a keyboard player in The Revolution. They are not the same dude! They even both appear in the movie Purple Rain, although only Fink has a speaking role and is part of The Kid's band (Dickerson appears briefly in a performance with his own band.) It's still a good and for the biggest part correct reference, barring some fine details, as far as I could discern when I looked up various stories for more information. And there were many stories I had never heard before; I had no idea that it recently came to light that Michael Hutchence of INXS suffered a head injury and brain damage in the early 90's which might shed some light of the troubles he had in the last few years of his life. And I did, at times, enjoy Wilson's snarky humor....more

review: I didn't finish this, so out of fairness I am not going to rate it. I made it about 1/3 of the way through this before I finally faced down the fact II didn't finish this, so out of fairness I am not going to rate it. I made it about 1/3 of the way through this before I finally faced down the fact I wasn't interested in picking it up anymore. It's not that it's bad really. I am a huge fan of King's first collection, Night Shift, and none of his other anthologies seem to reach those dizzying heights. This also falls into the era where I stopped reading King because his writing style grew stale and overly fussy: "I don't know how many people on the airliner just missed getting turned into strawberry jam, but I bet you do and I know the cockpit crew does. The only reason these guys are still alive is because the captain of that boat was bright enough to allemande right, and I was bright enough to d0-si-do...."I don't think this snippet can convey the weariness I have for how he could go on back then. I kind of speculate that he got too big to "need " editing and too many of his characters all had that same bloviating "I think I'm clever" affectation. People just don't talk like this. I did really like the first story, "Dolan's Cadillac", and as I said it's not bad. I'm a huge King fan, but this one might not be for me. I might also pick it up at a later date (In which case, future me: the last story I read was "Popsy".) BTW, King's having an amazing renaissance in the 2000's. I wholeheartedly recommend The Outsider and The Institute....more

title: And Don't F&%k It Up: An Oral History of RuPaul's Drag Race
author: Fernández, María Elena
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: (Psst, real quick before I get started, I fucking hate that this has to be a thing now but please consider supporting the ACLU's Drag Defense Fund bec(Psst, real quick before I get started, I fucking hate that this has to be a thing now but please consider supporting the ACLU's Drag Defense Fund because it's getting real ugly out there.) This will be the easiest  I ever write and you will ever read. Have you ever watched Drag Race ever or have you been curious about it or have you ever looked at this book and wondered if it's worth reading?If any of the above applies then, yes, hunty. This is the book for you.The first thing I want to get out of the way is this book was published in April of this year. Around the same time, the US version aired the finale of their 15th season and then their 8th season of All Stars. So, we're already behind, especially since All Stars is just touched on in the appendix. I assume more will be forthcoming, the first 10 seasons alone took up 400 pages, after all. The basic setup is a season a chapter, with a prefix, a very brief (as mentioned) All Stars chapter, no international seasons (the cheek, the nerve, the gall, the audacity and the gumption!), and some concluding words. It's an oral history so you hear from the dolls themselves plus production. It was lovely to hear the queens at least somewhat untethered from production control discuss what happened as they experienced it and it was also interesting to hear production talk about their side of things. Is it almost definitely tilted to make the show's creators look good? Duh. But it's still interesting to get their take on so many iconic moments.Great collection of voices, too, with multiple queens from each season and there is goopery and or gaggery on almost every page. Fun fact: just about every Season 9 queen claims that they were the first to recognize the last queen to enter the workroom was in fact THE Stefani Germanotta.Some queens I wish we could have heard from: Nina Bonina Brown, Alexis Michelle, Pearl (the stupid production feud with her needs to end), Willam (this stupid feud will never end and I both hate it and kind of live for it), Jade JolieQueens who were immediately identifiable even without context: Alyssa Edwards, Vanessa Vanjie Mateo, Laganja Estranja, Bob the Drag Queen, Bianca Del RioSpeaking of Laganja, I live for her getting a second chance with the fandom and hearing her side of things. And I agree with her, her roast set was unironically hysterical:[image]If she had said this to me, I would have fallen out of my chair, taken a Boniva, crawled back up and tipped her with everything in my purse. Hope the BluBlockers fit, Ganj!Look, I could keep babbling and gif the house down Versace boots take that thing off your face Gaga snatch my wig okurrr. But I'm not going to. Absolute must read. Here is producer Fenton Bailey reflecting on the show's legacy:One of the most moving things.....is seeing queens on the show who remember watching the show before they knew what they wanted to do with their creativity and it inspired them to do drag. That is so moving because gay people struggle to find their place in the world and it isn't easy to be your authentic self. I think that the very idea that people could watch this show....and then identify for themselves a career and a vocation and succeed at it.....is better than any Emmy....more

It, this union of verse full of wit, wryness and tragedy paired with the perfect horror film final girl, heroine, and anti-heroine.I ended up buying this and let me tell you, the price was a bargain because I will be re-reading this shit out of this. Snippets of some of my favorite lines:It always begins with the good intentions of men--Rosemary, Rosemary's Babyyour empathy. It's that sad, fragile, beautiful thing that will ruin you.--The Female (Part I), Under the SkinThere is nothing in this world like realizing you're going to live and not being sure you can.--Sally, The Texas Chainsaw MassacreTell me why I should mythologize this. Let his shape grow larger than the women crouched--Laurie, HalloweenDrink down dominion like milk, let it slither along the throat, that hard muscle for gulping—Heather, The WoodsYou might say things didn't end well, but I had fun. Ask anyone.--Ginger, Ginger SnapsI didn't connect with every poem, but I did highlight the shit out of this....more

review: Sometime around 8th or 9th grade, my friends and I learned that Judy Blume had at some point written a novel for adults called Wifey and it was dirrrtSometime around 8th or 9th grade, my friends and I learned that Judy Blume had at some point written a novel for adults called Wifey and it was dirrrty, hayyyyyy! We sat in the most isolated table we could find in our small town library and took turns reading it and far from the anticipated titillation, my thoughts amounted to "This is nothing like Forever..." and "Judy should stick to kids and teens." I decided then I was done with Judy's adult fiction. But then decades later I was in the Las Vegas airport and could not sit there reading my Kindle for one more goddamn minute. And I'm not going to make the most obvious Vegas joke but....I kind of did take a gamble and bought this from the sundries store. There's been so much press about how good it is lately. And....it's ok. The chief problem is it's way too freaking long. This story just doesn't have 400+ pages of steam. It's largely set on Martha's Vineyard, so it has vaguely Elin Hilderbrand vibes although it was published 2 years before Hilderbrand's first book and Elin Hilderbrand would never, ever write about 12 year old girls masturbating together.[image]ANYWAY, I did find this story about a complicated friendship between two young women that continues over decades, one rich and self-absorbed and one working class and good as gold--you know the drill--fitfully moving. The epilogue might have almost made me shed a single tear.But long before the end, I was kind of desperate for this to be over and don't really recommend it, although it might keep you just entertained enough on a long flight....more

author: Knoll, Jessica*
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: Right here, right now, I want you to forget two things: he was nothing special, and what happened was not random.This is very obviously the story of aRight here, right now, I want you to forget two things: he was nothing special, and what happened was not random.This is very obviously the story of a certain serial killer. If you haven't read the press blurbs, you'll almost immediately guess anyway because the first half includes a barely fictionalized retelling of the violent end of his crime spree in Florida and half of the story is narrated by an eyewitness at a certain sorority house. Because the author wants the story to be focused on the victims and survivors and not on the small, vain, dead sociopath responsible, she strips him of his name and so, then, will I. When Judge Edward Cowart sentenced THE DEFENDENT in his first capital murder trial, he referred to him as a "bright young man." This book will challenge that notion, repeatedlyPhewww. It was tough, tough, TOUGH reading this book and I contemplated putting it aside more than once in the first half but I persevered through and I'm....I don't know if glad is the right word exactly, maybe happy that I persevered. I felt physically ill, sad, and so angry through much of it. But more objectively, I desperately wished that Knoll had included some kind of afterword to help separate fact from fiction.  I think it would have bolstered some of her claims because as it turns out she did so much research, reading through hundreds of pages of trial transcripts (during the pandemic, no less) and speaking to one survivor of the Chi Omega murders. Here, for example, is Knoll on her Instagram reading an excerpt of THE DEFENDENT's nearly inarticulate closing statement that rambled on for some 45 minutes. (But despite much reluctant Googling about this case and learning waaaay more than I everrr needed to know, I still don't know if there is any truth to some other allegations in the book. For example, is the stuff about the DA in Colorado factual?) Still, in spite of the somewhat slow first half and the somewhat uneasy feeling at first that Knoll was resting on the subject matter to do most of the heavy lifting, I was eventually won over and marveled many times at how well she captured the souls of these lost women and how this violence is like a tear in space/time. These women and girls were here, they had lives, they had purpose, they should still be here but they are gone. Excerpts that show Knoll at her finest:I was thinking about Denise and all the people she encountered in her daily life. The woman who sold Denise the multivitamin that made her hair healthy and strong and the family with the dog Denise sometimes walked for a little extra cash and the saleswoman at Denise's favorite clothing store in Tallahassee who always set things aside she thought Denise would like. I was wondering who would tell all these people that Denise was dead and if it should be me.*******I wondered where we were and what we were doing when he decided on us. I understood in a new way why premeditation carried a stiffer sentence than crimes that occurred in the heat of the moment. It was a unique kind of violation to think that when you were curled up on the couch, watching As the World Turns with your best friend, someone was plotting your demise. I found I was having difficulty swallowing.*******The hope is that when we come back in the fall, one of the ferns will flag Ruth's final resting place. But I can do better than hope. I have faith because nature is the very best example of integration. Things grow differently when they're damaged, showing us how to occupy strange new ground to bloom red instead of green. We can be found, brighter than before....more

For now at least, all but two are available on Kindle Unlimited. Ok, mommy, I love you but this was....meh. First of all, I get it. Probably not a lot of cash for an editor:Her whole body hummed and buzzed with the vibration of the forest. Max had never felt more ecstatic, more real, in her entire life......Max's whole body hummed.If I could figure out a way to count how many times something hummed, which I'm too lazy to do, it would be, I don't know, like a bunch. That would also make me kind of a dick. I guess I'm already being kind of a dick tho. Not really scary and too earnest to be dark humor which makes the denouement all the more “The fuck?”, this is a tale of some teenage girls who decide to fuck up their local representatives of the patriarchy. I want to say a little more about this because I’m tired and clearly I’m at the babbling stage. I can remember teenage boys being assholes. But you know who else are assholes? Teenage girls. I remember in 11th grade my friend Lisa got someone to cut her hair so she had a tail—it was all the rage at the time. Except hers was just a big chunk of hair in the back that was longer than the rest. Then she died it blonde, so now she had a big chunk of hair in the back that was longer than the rest that looked like it got lost on the way back to someone else’s head.So when we were in chemistry class and JP Morgan was making fun of her hair and he looked at me and said, “Vanessa, tell her it looks stupid.” and then Lisa turned around to look at me, did I defend her hairdo’s honor? No, I started giggling (see? I was the asshole in that story.)(view spoiler)[Case in point, the most fucked up thing that is done to the protagonist in this story is by a teenage girl at her school, who put a dead bird in her hair (which the protagonist didn't notice for a while, how the HELL do you miss having a rotting carcass on your head?) But it's a boy from her school who got human sacrificed at the end. (hide spoiler)]My point is, girl, this is overkill.ETA: So I wrote this about two hours before the food poisoning gurgling away in my stomach made a legendary appearance, so I think that's likely why this  has such a delirious, rambling quality. Since I still agree with the sentiments, I'm keeping it....more

review: Do I feel normal? I asked myself. Like a normal twenty-three-year-old? Like a normal person? The answer was no. I knew it would always be, and I was fDo I feel normal? I asked myself. Like a normal twenty-three-year-old? Like a normal person? The answer was no. I knew it would always be, and I was foolish to hope for anything different. Hope is like candy, I thought. It's sweet in the moment, until it rots your teeth out. My past would always be my past. My family would always be my family. So I'd never be fucking normal.Y'all, I bought this on a whim and was not--NOT--prepared for how much I would love this. Sure, the subject matter was right up my alley, can't go into details of course. And sure, I've seen a lot of horror movies with this trope and as other ers have mentioned, you'll likely guess what is going on before various reveals occur. Or maybe you won't, I don't know your life. Regardless, my opinion is it doesn't matter because this was a pure blast to read. A lord over all that flies blast.The one thing I was thought might be a reveal and blessedly wasn't was (view spoiler)[I thought maybe Vesper's new boss George would turn out to be Lucifer in disguise and when they hooked up I was like that is so metal of you, Rachel Harrison, but also fuck, shit, shittt! They are actually having sex and that means she is banging the Devil aka Dad, what in the Rosemary's Elektra Complex Baby, NOOOOO!. (hide spoiler)]But back to the beginning. Vesper was raised in a weird, secretive cult in rural New Jersey until she ran away at 18. But life in the outside world, while free of cult life and her mother, who is a B movie scream queen and, also, a bitch, is anti-climactic. When Vesper receives a mysterious wedding invite for the marriage of her cousin and childhood sweetheart and an offer to return home, she can't resist the adamantine bonds of the past. It's not like they will miss her at the soul-sucking chain restaurant where she works, especially since she just got fired.It's kind of weird they are just welcoming her home though, since people who leave are typically shunned for life. Oh well, nothing to worry about, I'm sure. It's not like there's an adversary there waiting for her.I thought this was smart, I thought it was clever how Harrison worked in a lot of real world thoughts about how your family doesn't have to define you, and while I took a bit of time to warm up, I loved Vesper and was rooting for her in the fucking insane climax which made me want to cry and cheer at the same time. I used to confuse Rachel Harrison with Kim Harrison, an urban fantasy author who wrote a series about a character named Rachel, but now I know who Rachel Harrison is and I'm admittedly a wee bit obsessed with her....more

author: Hilderbrand, Elin*

review: She squeezes her hand, and for the first time ever in her life, Jessie understands that her mother is real.It's a revelation. Her mother is a human beShe squeezes her hand, and for the first time ever in her life, Jessie understands that her mother is real.It's a revelation. Her mother is a human being who feels pain--sadness, loneliness, confusion. Jessie thought all grown-ups lived in a different atmosphere, one that was like a cool, clear gel. Adults had problems, Jessie knew--money and their children--but one of the benefits of reaching adulthood, she thought, was that you outgrew the raw, hot, chaotic emotions of adolescence.Ok, after years of seeing her on the best seller charts (and eventually realizing this was not Tiger Woods' wife), I have read my first Elin Hilderbrand and I loved it. Like really loved it. I laughed, I cried, I tried to blame it on menopause but, no. This is a genuinely greatly written book full of achingly relatable life moments even if your family doesn't summer on Nantucket--I assure you mine does not. I'm also not a fan of romance novels (which this isn't) or beach reads (which this is) but I loved this anyway. Elin Hilderbrand can write, y'all! This prose is gorgeous, the way the story is put together is sneakily brilliant and I spent 10 minutes on FaceTime the other night telling my unenthused mom the Foley-Levin family has got to pay more attention to little Jessie for shit's sakes!! I was so invested in these people. When the summer of 1969 starts, Kate Levin must send her only son to Vietnam leading to a tumultuous but ultimately life-changing summer for everyone (I'm going to pause here and say that Hildebrand's "brand" is comfort reads of a sort so don't start noping out, even if she doesn't mince words about the horrors of that war.) Kate struggles with perpetual agonizing worry about her son, Tiger, and finds drinking is the only way to manage it. Oldest daughter Blair is pregnant and learning almost immediately post-wedding that marriage wasn't what she thought. Middle daughter Kirby underneath her blustering exterior is aching to find herself and plans to rebel by spending the summer on....Martha's Vineyard. And the youngest, Jessie, is going through a lot too and for shit's sakes, would you people pay more attention TO JESSIE??Ok, Jessie clearly was my favorite, maybe because her sections of the book gave me luminous Judy Blume vibes: bright, sensitive, and Jewish because of her father (the rest of the kids are from Kate's first marriage) and missing her brother horribly while dealing with a first love that feels so real it made my face sting and a creepy tennis instructor and spending her first summer at her grandmother's house without her siblings. Kid, I am rooting for you.When she was a child, she told her parents everything: I'm hungry, I'm tired, I need to use the bathroom, I skinned my knee, I like, I hate, I want, I need. What if growing up means keeping some things to herself? The experiences of this summer will become as much a part of her as her bones and muscle, her brain and heart. Ten or twenty years from now, when she looks back on the summer of 1969, she will think: That was the summer I became real. My own real person......And then another radical thought strikes her: to her father, she is already a real person.[image]Oh! I didn't realize you were there. Pardon me, someone must be burning trash, my eyes are watering. From some reading I've done (Elin Hilderbrand, like me, was born in 1969, she attended the Iowa Writer's Workshop but dropped out, she lives on Nantucket year round), this book seems to be listed as a lot of reader's favorite. I've read a few of the other book descriptions and wasn't sure I was interested, but Hilderbrand is mad prolific and I'm definitely ready to read more. Also, if you are interested in these characters, Hilderbrand wrote a follow-up story "Summer of '79" that is available as an e-book or audiobook....more

title: The Outlaw Album
author: Woodrell, Daniel
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: Daniel Woodrell is best known for writing the novel Winter's Bone (which was turned into a movie that was Jennifer Lawrence's break-through role), butDaniel Woodrell is best known for writing the novel Winter's Bone (which was turned into a movie that was Jennifer Lawrence's break-through role), but there is more, much more, worth exploring in his catalog. That includes this small collection of short stories, many published originally in them fancy literary journals, about scallawags and small tragedies. All are set in the Ozarks, where he's from and still resides. Like other ers, I felt like the beginning was the strongest, but there wasn't a story I didn't like (maybe "The Horse in Our History" came close.) Here are some of the best, with quotes to set the Woodrell mood.Uncle--a young woman takes justice into her own hands to save herself and her mother from a rotted relative, leading her to ponder the nature of evil. This was my favorite.He was helpless, and I took to wondering if Uncle was still evil now that he'd become a helpless baby. Do babies learn evil in the run of their days, or bring it with them from the other side of all that you can see?Black Step--a Gulf War veteran ponders life back home and finds it wanting. Not the life he has so much as being alive in general.They tell me Dad committed suicide for reasons he dreamed up. His mind was too active. He had a round mind and it roamed. He could imagine the many miseries of this world flying over from everywhere to roost between his ears, but he couldn't imagine how to get away.Florianne--while most of his stories have their funny moments (black humored though they may often be), this is a wrenching tale about a father living with the long time unsolved disappearance of his daughter.At some point every old friend sensed my suspicion aim their way and several couldn't get over that moment of recognition, even after my suspicion rotated to the next ol' buddy, or slightly creepy cousin, that mailman with the pencil mustache.....I've often thought about that: If she'd stayed chunky would she be here now? Some questions popping up keep the hurt fresh....more

title: The Rachel Incident
author: O'Donoghue, Caroline*
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: That spring was different, though, because James and I were the hopeful green shoots, pushing up through frozen earth with brand-new velocity.Rachel lThat spring was different, though, because James and I were the hopeful green shoots, pushing up through frozen earth with brand-new velocity.Rachel lives in the present in London, an ex-pat Irish journalist who is married and seriously pregnant and determinedly looking forward. But when she learns through a chance encounter at a bar that her old college professor is in a coma, she is catapulted back 10 years to when she was a university student in Cork and the complicated relationship between her, her professor, and her best friend James. "Whenever anyone has, like, an exciting romantic life, I'm all over it." Exciting romantic life! When I couldn't even make Carey shag me in a bread shop.I was fully not prepared for how gorgeously written this book is and how it felt to experience so potently that time of your life again when you are an adult but not really and having the first adult friendships that will change who you are and you are constantly fucking up because you haven't figured out how to not fuck up and how exciting and terrifying and heartbreaking and amazing and precious it all is and I loved this book so much for taking me back there. "Sometimes I feel like I was in a coma or something, before we met."God...I, ok I said the stuff about fucking up already, did I? I remember this, I remember how this felt. But I'm also decades older than these characters so I also want to hug them and shelter them and tell them it will all be ok and how I know it's hard but please run after that person and chose your words better because this might be the only moment you have to make it right. "Like"--he fiddled with the string edges of the blanket--"you know, people like me, I'm funny. I can write jokes. I can always get laid. I can always make a living. I can always get a job. That's a lot, you know?"He braided the pieces of string together. "That's a lot for one person to have. I think it's ok if I never get to have, like, romantic love."Ok, I am slightly watery eyed at that quote but I'm not going to cry, goddamnit, (I blame menopause--can I blame menopause??) because this isn't a sad book. It has sad moments, certainly, and moments so intentionally cringe that your pancreas will flip inside out but it's really, really lovely and warm and funny and Caroline O'Donoghue can string prose together and make beauty page after page after page. I will hereon read anything with her name on it....more

title: The Program: Inside the Mind of Keith Raniere and the Rise and Fall of NXIVM
author: Natalie, Toni
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: They are all martyrs to the cause, all expendable.But not me. Not Toni Natalie.I'm the one who got away.So if anyone remembers that crazy news story aThey are all martyrs to the cause, all expendable.But not me. Not Toni Natalie.I'm the one who got away.So if anyone remembers that crazy news story about some self-help cult in New York state that was branding women a few years ago, this is a story about them. The one that had the actress from Smallville (Allison Mack) in it and Catherine Oxenberg's daughter, India? If you saw the HBO documentary, "The Vow", Toni Natalie was featured in season 1 and (briefly, I think) in season 2. This is her memoir of her time spent with Raniere in the years leading up to the creation of NXIVM and his adoption of the moniker "Vanguard" (named after an arcade game he used to play) and the literal decades of torment she endured from his minions for having the audacity to reject him:"And, Toni?""Yes?""You need to start calling him Vanguard."Vanguard. Like he was a hunky member of the Justice League and not a megalomaniacal con man who looked like Rick Moranis. I laughed in her face."Fuck that," I said.In what became the NXIVM playbook (borrowed heavily from Scientology), Toni was subjected to endless harassment after she left: her home was broken into multiple times, her mail was stolen, her dog was poisoned, she and her family were bankrupted by an avalanche of nuisance lawsuits, and most bizarrely, with assistance from higher-ups in NXIVM Mexico, a plan was hatched to lure her and other "enemies", including cult de-programmer Rick Ross, to Mexico where they would be thrown into jail and tortured/murdered. Fortunately, the "smartest man in the world" and his inner circle were largely dumbasses. And Toni Natalie?Toni Natalie is a fucking badass. And because she was there in the early years (she was the one who introduced Keith Raniere to Nancy Saltzman, the heads of NXIVM who are currently both in prison), she knows these people well and has a lot of insight to share. Or gossip, some would say. Regardless of what you call it, girl, I was living:Keith already had disciples, but his "girls" all had flaws. Pam was a space cadet, too flighty and dim to stand with him. Kristin was too headstrong, and didn't bring enough expertise to the table. Karen had the brains and the capacity for evil but lacked the charisma....While he had wooed me as a lover and partner however, he had failed to convert me to the Church of Keith.Gossip/insight with a heavy splash of vinegar, I should add. If anyone has earned this, it's Toni. This book covers the period right up to Keith's guilty verdict and the indictment of his co-conspirators and since Toni followed the trial closely and often in person, you'll learn lots of interesting, sometimes schadenfreude-laden and hilarious, tidbits from that time as well:Her [Clare Bronfman's] attorney at the time, Susan Necheles, was a hot mess: frustrated, interrupting the judge......After the hearing, Necheles was unable to find her car, leaving Clare to wander the streets while photographers snapped her picture.So, to summarize--Is this worth reading?As you might have guessed, I have gone down a deep rabbit hole with this story and I still found this book interesting. Toni was an insider from the start, often reluctantly. This is perspective no one else has. I also think you can easily follow this without knowing the extensive backstory. I want to read ONE book/watch one documentary about NXIVM. Is this it?No, you should definitely read Don't Call It a Cult: The Shocking Story of Keith Raniere and the Women of NXIVM by Sarah Berman.In conclusion:  Natalie and her ghost writer, reporter Chet Hardin, write well and succinctly and the snark really is the icing. I'm not sure if this is a four star read for everyone, but I got four stars of entertainment out of it....more

review: Most of the time, I love a Ruth Ware mystery. But sometimes, things happen.A brief scan of s shows a lot of people agree with me on this one. WeMost of the time, I love a Ruth Ware mystery. But sometimes, things happen.A brief scan of s shows a lot of people agree with me on this one. We appreciate Ruth was trying something new, but it took too long to get going, wasn't that engaging, and the killer is....well, I think you'll figure it out. I didn't DNF as some others did because I'd already spent the first 100 pages reading almost solely about the main character's grief and while it was written well, I am not into wading through all of that unless we are talking a seriously literary mystery, like anything by Dennis Lehane or Long Bright River by Liz Moore. But I did flip around a bit. I just wanted to land this plane and get on with my life, y'all. Ruth Ware novels I confidently recommend:* The Death of Mrs. Westaway* One by One* In a Dark, Dark Wood* The Turn of the KeyRuth, I still heart you. ...more

title: Give Us a Kiss

my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: Niagra, so full of scrumptious hope, is looking at me, there, afraid I won't share her vision. She's afraid I'll tell her that the world won't let herNiagra, so full of scrumptious hope, is looking at me, there, afraid I won't share her vision. She's afraid I'll tell her that the world won't let her have her dreams realized quite so easily, and probably not at all. That her dream is just a thread of fantasy to hang by for a while, but it'll go limp one horrid night somewhere down life's road and start coiling around her pretty neck. But I don't want to tell her...Because those young dream-years are by far the best years, when you have hardy faith and gallops of energy and go for it all, perhaps in a dumb fashion but with gusto, right up 'til the night the dreams goes limp and starts that coil.Where were you when the dream went limp? Daniel Woodrell is probably best known for writing Winter's Bone, source of the movie with Jennifer Lawrence. I read that book over 10 years ago and loved it. The movie captured the plot but not the plain spoken, sometimes gloriously vulgar, often transcendent tone of Woodrell's writing. Reading his prose is like swooning, repeatedly, and wanting to grab a highlighter but you'd highlight damn near the whole book. This is a story about Doyle Redmond, an Ozark boy from West Table, Missouri, (a stand in for the author's hometown, West Plains, a recurring location in Woodrell's work) A charming shitkicker with a poet's soul, Doyle has tried to make it as a glossy yet earthy literary type and even made it to the Iowa Writer's Workshop but has remained obscure and never quite ditched his shitkicker roots (Doyle, also, shares at least some of his life story with Woodrell.) So when his marriage hits the skids, he borrows (more or less, probably less) his wife's prize Volvo and heads back east and finds himself on an errand back to West Table to get his older brother Smoke out of trouble. But it turns out neither brother are much invested in that errand and much more invested in a huge marijuana crop Smoke and his girlfriend Big Annie are clandestinely growing in the woods. Doyle is also instantly invested in Big Annie's daughter, Niagra, an otherworldly beauty with an oddball intellect.Smooching at the Dog'NSuds, my class ring worn on a string around a girl's neck, parents who just didn't understand--I'd never been there. Now here I was, having a sort of teenage love affair, only I was thirty-five years old having it, and hear this clear--it was everything common legend had glossed it up to be, and more. But full of hidden shoals.(Hear this clear: the way Woodrell writes is like sunlit honey in your mouth.)Alas, there is trouble on the wind in this hawthorn and cannabis-scented Ozark paradise: the local bad element know the Redmond brothers are up to something in the woods and have been skulking around looking for any opportunity to make mendacity. And as the money garden continues to ripen, the dread does as well as you wait for bad shit to manifest. Recurring Woodrell themes of land and family resonate here, not just of those things in the present but the eternal endurance of those things and the celestial destiny that binds you to both. He's also a genius at making you love small time cons. Maybe Doyle and Smoke are lovable because they're the protagonists, but their steadfast commitment to each other and their own brand of mud-and-blood-spattered chivalry make them a pair you can't help but love, as long as they aren't your neighbors. Do you like grit lit? Are you interested in hillbilly noir? Do you like writing that can turn an anecdote about the dates on pennies into a tragedy of Aristotelian proportions? Then you-YOU!-need Daniel Woodrell in your life....more

review: A simple thing can turn you into a monster.This was more like a 3.5 for me for the story, but the message is a solid 4: patriotism that has slipped thA simple thing can turn you into a monster.This was more like a 3.5 for me for the story, but the message is a solid 4: patriotism that has slipped the rails, uncertain times, and fairy tales can easily ignite into real-world mayhem. Any similarities to January 6th or Pizzagate are purely intentional. It's very near the end of World War II in a German village in the Reindhardswald region of Germany, home of the Sleeping Beauty Castle, the origins of some famous Brothers Grimm stories, and fantastical forests. Uwe Fuchs is a decent man with a young family. He quietly dislikes the Nazis and mistrusts what the government says about the war's success. But he also worries about the rumors about Allied troops murdering all Germans they find. He also struggles with feelings of being an inadequate protector and conflicting loyalties toward the Fatherland. This allows him to be drawn into bad company with even worse ideas. And you can guess where that leads-[image]How you gonna keep em down on Der Bauernhof when they can't keep their eyeballs in their heads?Alma Katsu is well-known amongst horror fans for writing stories that are grounded in a historical setting that's purposefully chosen (she also writes the Red Widow series.) I loved the thick atmosphere of the time and place and enjoyed the odd bits of history. In Nazi Germany, the Grimm fairy tales were a propaganda weapon so valuable that every home was required to have a copy. "Little Red Riding Hood" became an allegory for how the Jews kept the German people down and "Cinderella" was transformed into an homage to Aryan beauty. It's a novella so the ending is somewhat abrupt, but this was a good story with a great message that might have become repetitive over a novel's length but worked fine here....more

review: A half hour later the three of us left the room for the lobby. Lula on one side of me, Connie on the other...Connie and Lula now wore two guns apiece.A half hour later the three of us left the room for the lobby. Lula on one side of me, Connie on the other...Connie and Lula now wore two guns apiece. They each had a gun at the small of their back and they each had one in their purse. My fear of getting shot by the Carnation Killer was considerably less than my fear that I'd get shot by Connie or Lula.Stephanie Plum returns in her ninth outing, her world preserved in golden amber with top notes of Love's Baby Soft and Cheez-It's. There's a soothing consistency to this series, even as it strains credulity: Stephanie is still not great at her job, Morelli and Ranger are in a frosty detente over their carnal but loving impulses toward her, and Ranger and Lula are constantly helping Stephanie perform her bounty huntering without complaint or (apparently) compensation (which is really the most unbelievable part to me.)This time, Vinnie is on the hook for some new type of immigration bond when the bondee, Samuel Singh, vanishes. All of Vinnie's employees are told to give this top priority so Stephanie sets out to comb Trenton looking for Singh and his landlord's missing dog. Along the way, she attracts the attention of a possible serial killer and before you can say "I'm president of the Lisa Lisa and Cult Jam Fan Club, yes there still is one excuse your mouth," she's getting weird messages, even worse photos, and potential witnesses keep dropping dead. There are plenty of funny bits to this story of course--Lula tries an Atkins Diet type thing with farcical results, Lula, Connie, and Stephanie take a paid trip to Vegas, and Stephanie is always Stephanie. I didn't find this one as funny as some of the last few books. Evanovich more often than not lands her slapstick humor but too often here she drives right past ridiculous but funny and lands in plain ridiculous.And while I can forgive a lot of improbable things in this series, it was too much when (view spoiler)[Stephanie, who KNOWS she's being stalked by a wackadoo serial killer, loans her sister Valerie and poor Albert Kloughn her apartment. Oh, they also have a newborn. (hide spoiler)]For that matter, the main mystery plot is pretty out there too ((view spoiler)[a bunch of losers are playing a game trying to assassinate each other IRL and win prizes but the guy running the game decides they should kill Stephanie as well because he's into her, so he sends someone to kill her but then decides he actually wants to kill her himself? IDK, I'm glad Stephanie shot the shit out of him. His motive was fucking stupid. (hide spoiler)]) But, these books are all about the mood you are in when you read them. They are light and slapsticky; maybe I wasn't in the mood for slapstick. They are strangely addictive though and as of this writing there are 29 books in the series so I can rest assured Stephanie will rally and be around when I need her....more

title: Uncovering Greek Mythology: A Beginner's Guide into the World of Greek Gods and Goddesses        (Ancient History Book 2)
author: Russo, Lucas
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: This was a Kindle Unlimited find and it's a good and thorough refresher of Greek mythology. I like some of the original approaches the author took to This was a Kindle Unlimited find and it's a good and thorough refresher of Greek mythology. I like some of the original approaches the author took to the material, like explaining the significance of various plants in myth. For instance, Persephone created mint when she shredded a nymph who was trying to seduce Hades; it's kind of weird Persephone would get jealous when she was only married to Hades because he had kidnapped her and dragged her to the underworld but those gods and demi-gods were a wacky emo bunch.I also enjoyed the author giving more context (and therefore, ironically, humanity) to the Gods' actions, as in this passage about Hera:It is easy to dismiss her reactions against Zeus, his mortal lovers, and illegitimate children...but we must keep in mind that Hera above all, as a deity symbolizing marriage and family, is a representation of stability.I did find the material dry at times (although, have you tried reading Hamilton's Mythology recently? Talk about dry) and the writing was occasionally clunky. But I learned a lot and highlighted the crap out of this book to the point where I figured I might as well buy it. I'm sure the people I buttonhole in the future while I explain the origin of the mint plant will be so grateful. The author, Lucas Russo, has a whole series about ancient mythology, including volumes on Egyptian and Norse, if you are interested in the subject....more

review: I discovered Angie Kim via Book of the Month Club. I really loved her first book, Miracle Creek, so to start out, that is a more satisfying read in myI discovered Angie Kim via Book of the Month Club. I really loved her first book, Miracle Creek, so to start out, that is a more satisfying read in my opinion.Like many second novels, this book repeats themes of the first book (one such example, the Korean immigrant experience in America), digs deeper into those topics, and adopts a more challenging, zigzag course. I'm very conflicted. The narrator of this story, 20 year old Mia, has such a unique, compelling voice. I simply don't think I've ever encountered anyone quite like her in fiction before. And Angie Kim writes so beautifully. This story is a mystery but it's wrapped in literary fiction about a family in crisis and also wants to examine the interactions between disabilities (and, in a broader sense, "otherness") and the justice system. I love novels that do more than one thing. The problem for me was the way Kim brought that last topic into play caused the story to slalom down a path of increasingly unbelievable (and, frankly, weird) plot points, especially when it comes to (view spoiler)[Eugene's alibi (hide spoiler)], until it started to fly off the rails around 50 pages from the end. I hate to say this, but despite the many things I loved, I'm left with an ending that was unsatisfying. However, reading is an individual experience and that's especially true here. I am neither Korean nor have a family member with Angelman Syndrome, for example. I will definitely still read the next Angie Kim....more

title: Evidence of Things Seen
author: Weinman, Sarah
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: I stumbled upon Sarah Weinman's previous collection of crime journalism, Unspeakable Acts: True Tales of Crime, Murder, Deceit, and Obsession, by chanI stumbled upon Sarah Weinman's previous collection of crime journalism, Unspeakable Acts: True Tales of Crime, Murder, Deceit, and Obsession, by chance in a bookstore and I still think about stories in it often. Weinman considers this book--whose title is inspired by James Baldwin's book Evidence of Things Not Seen, about the Atlanta child murders--a companion to the first one and it's going to hit hard and repeatedly at the beliefs of a lot of readers, my own included. The overarching theme most of these tales have in common is "Who gets to tell our stories?" Some articles are better than others and at least one I thought was too long, but there isn't a bad, or even mediocre, one in the bunch. In fact, there are SO MANY brilliant articles here that it's hard to single out a few favorites but I'll try:"A Brutal Lynching. An Indifferent Police Force. A 34-Year Wait for Justice" by Wesley Lowery"How the Atlanta Spa Shootings-the Victims, the Survivors-Tell a Story of America" by May Jeong"Picturesque California Conceals a Crisis of Missing Indigenous Women" by Brandi Morin"The Prisoner-Run Radio Station That's Reaching Men on Death Row" by Keri Blakinger"Has Reality Caught Up to the Murder Police?" by Lara Bazelon (If you watched Homicide or The Wire, prepare to be really depressed)The appendix of further books, articles, and podcasts is huge. I'm still tempted to take some pictures of it. "Social justice" is a much used and abused term these days but this book talks about it and it's impossible to ignore. ...more

title: The Guest
author: Cline, Emma
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: Alex had not taken the credit card, not taken the money clip, and who would notice the fifties were gone, or the measly silver barrette, amongst all tAlex had not taken the credit card, not taken the money clip, and who would notice the fifties were gone, or the measly silver barrette, amongst all that abundance. The universe had protected Alex....There was no reason to feel anxious--the fear had been transmuted, the way it often was, into excitement, the memory always dissolving until it was only the idea of fear, and when had the idea of fear ever been a convincing deterrent?Rating this book bedevils me, as ratings sometimes do. I really like Emma Cline's writing and this book is very Emma Cline, dealing with "agency, cost, the performance of gender, the undercurrent of violence roiling just beneath the surface of ordinary life." (In honor of the sticky fingered protagonist of this novel, I just stole that line from "the Paris Review's interview with Cline.) If you've even glanced at the other s, this is a divisive book. And as much as I like Emma Cline's writing, this felt like a slog although it absolutely got much better in the second half and I had to see how this ended AND it will linger in my brain for a long time.Why it's so hard to read has largely to do with a somewhat opaque and extremely unlikable (but brilliantly conjured) protagonist and a languid plot that could almost seem like not much is happening, although that's not really the case. "Why are you like this?" asks one exasperated kind-hearted soul who has the misfortune of getting entangled briefly with Alex. And we would like to know that too, although perhaps the point is sometimes there just is no reason. Some people are just toxic jellyfish, drifting through life without a purpose beyond survival, not intending malice exactly but always leaving shrug-laden disaster in their wake. When Alex is booted from latest trophy girlfriend status from her latest wealthy boyfriend, she convinces herself that he is only angry with her and resolves to spend a week on Long Island scraping by until his Labor Day Party where they will magically reunite and she will return to a life with endless days of leisure and high thread count sheets. Yeah, this idea is laughable, but she can't examine that too closely because she has a looong trail of burnt bridges behind her (including an unsavory ex she's ripped off) and nowhere to go. And so this book recounts her week spent in various Hamptons careening from one port in the storm to another, just waiting for Labor Day where her future will magically re-manifest. What makes this story worth it is Emma Cline's writing and her thoughts of what separates the likes of Alex from the idle rich:"I'm sure they do," Alex said, "I'm sure they care." Though, as she said it, she didn't believe it was true. Even for people like Jack, with parents like his. Or the kids at the party the night before. Hundreds of years ago, their parents might have abandoned their babies in the woods. Instead, the neglect was stretched out over many years, a slow motion withering. The kids were still abandoned, still neglected in the woods, but the forest was lovely.Not my favorite Emma Cline (that would be The Girls) but still absolutely brimming with her jittery energy and bravely unafraid to walk in the shoes of unlikable but complex and fascinating characters....more

review: Ehhhh.Ok. I....ehhhhhhhhhh.I didn't realize when I reserved this it was from Tor, I generally find their books underwhelming (although NOT the MurderbEhhhh.Ok. I....ehhhhhhhhhh.I didn't realize when I reserved this it was from Tor, I generally find their books underwhelming (although NOT the Murderbot series, Murderbot is awesome.) In this space horror novella, a generation ship is limping and listing back to Earth after their attempt at colonizing went belly up. They've got some problems, like the interstellar conflict they seem to have wandered into, their dwindling food stores, and inability to contact the rest of their rag tag fleet. But it gets worse when it appears there is a murdery monster on the ship. But, dear reader, be prepared for the most terrifying revelation of them all: Hey, this story is sounding awfully familiar…Holy Leviathan! What in the Deep Star Six could it be? Please withhold the Terror Within as all is revealed beneath the spoiler tag, because I'm not a monster.We're on an express elevator to Hell, going down in 3, 2, 1, mark. (view spoiler)[[image]Oh look, it's a xenomorph. Actually a handful of them, complete with eggs. They use the ventilation system to travel around. There's an android who may or may not be evil. And a Ripley, who will once again blast them out of the goddamn airlock (more or less.)Basically, this was Alien franchise stew. The writing is ok, the characters are kind of flat. There is a twist in the last quarter but that doesn't make this original enough for me. Teenagers who have no reference to this all being done better before might like it. (hide spoiler)]...more

review: As of this fleeting moment in time, I have read every Riley Sager novel. But every summer for the past several years he comes out with a new thriller As of this fleeting moment in time, I have read every Riley Sager novel. But every summer for the past several years he comes out with a new thriller that is usually a fun mish-mash of a popular trope thrown in multiple blenders. Pages will be turned and midnight oil will be burned. In this entry, Kit McDeere is a home health aide who is currently unemployed because people think she either killed or assisted in the suicide of her last patient. Forced to accept the only job she is offered, she winds up working high above the Maine coastline at a crumbling estate that is the site of an infamous triple homicide in the 1920's (the story takes place in the early 80's.) Her patient is the even more infamous supposed killer: Lenora Hope, who has a Lizzy Borden-esque rhyme the local children repeat to tell the story of how she bumped off her family one night in 1929. It turns out there are other mysteries at the house and, even worse, the structure is architecturally unsound and is rapidly sliding off the edge of the cliff. But Kit can't get hired anywhere else and has nowhere else to go anyway. Then shit starts happening. So, credit where credit is due, this IS a page turner. You'll definitely want to finish it fast. But will you find it all believable when you are done?Schmaayybe. So many revelations rain down near the end I had to stop more than once to flip back and go, "Wait...how....?" Sager eventually explains them all but I still wasn't totally satisfied. And I want to talk briefly about our protagonist, Kit. Despite driving the point home that she has no money and no other job prospects, repeatedly, she goes out of her way to tell her patient that she's scared of her and offends the other staff on the first day and then just keeps on saying more dumb stuff. And she's in her 30's. She's worked as a home caregiver for several years. She should be smarter than this. I feel there's a way to make this story still work and hum at a rapid clip without having such a perpetually and, more importantly, unrealistically foot-in-mouth protagonist. I did enjoy the surprisingly heartwarming way this wrapped up but this is not peak Riley Sager. Wait, what is? I gotchu.Must reads:Final GirlsThe Last Time I LiedHome Before DarkWill entertain, at least:Lock Every DoorThe House Across the LakeBozo no-noSurvive the Night...more

review: He glanced at me. "You were sent by Artemis. It was Hera, the queen of the immortals, who gave this task to me. I won't defy her."But Hera wouldn't saHe glanced at me. "You were sent by Artemis. It was Hera, the queen of the immortals, who gave this task to me. I won't defy her."But Hera wouldn't save him, I thought. Artemis has show me that the gods could be as ruthless to their favorites as they were to their enemies. Jason thought that Hera's blessing was the same as her protection. He didn't see that she had merely given him the chance to succeed. If he failed her, it would be better he die than survive long enough to face her disappointment. But he knew nothing of the gods. Jason thought the world was built for heroes. I knew we had to build it ourselves.Ok, so, I liked this but I didn’t love this, although I do love Atalanta and the tiny cadre of ass-kicking mythological women she reps for. And that’s down to liking the message here (being a girl who makes her own rules and wants to do the things boys do can be hard and lonely) more than the delivery.Stories of Atalanta differ, because that's how mythology goes, but this version does stick to the best beats of the Atalanta myths: she was abandoned in the woods as an infant by her father who wanted a boy, she was spared a grim fate by Artemis, she was a legendarily fast runner, a deadly archer, and stronger than most men. She was a bonafide Argonaut and she killed the famous Calydonian boar. She was also a favorite companion of Artemis until she fell out of favor (which really wasn't hard to do with Artemis. Even a relatively feminist goddess like her has pretty regressive rules about women and consent.)[image]This is how our fleet of foot legend Atalanta is often depicted. Try not to focus too much on how well or swift she was gonna run without a foundation garment.The story sounds exciting but it really dragged in places as some of the quests end up being anti-climactic and, to be fair, that is how mythological stories are told some times. Like all set up ("We landed the boat and this army of six-armed giants with chainsaws for arms and laser beam eyes attacked us") and little to no payoff (".....so, uh, we like threw rocks at their leaders' head and he exploded so they all ran away.") As much as I love Atalanta, my eyes were crossing with boredom at points.(The best part was when Medea enters the tale with her chaotic neutral witch vibes. I NEED a Medea retelling.)I also thought it was an odd choice to (view spoiler)[spend SO much time with Meleager, whom Atalanta clearly had a connection with, only to kill him off and have her meet back up with Hippomenes who gets less than half the story that Meleager gets. I get we’re supposed to think Hippomenes is more compatible with how she lived, but that just didn’t come across. (hide spoiler)]I thought the way the story was resolved was brilliant (view spoiler)[basically, Atalanta can only live as she chooses as a female warrior if she's not a human female (hide spoiler)] and that bit gave me a lot to think about, the way the best myths can....more

review: The Darker family is gathered for their matriarch's 80th birthday on a small island off the Cornish coast that is only accessible at low tide. Boy, itThe Darker family is gathered for their matriarch's 80th birthday on a small island off the Cornish coast that is only accessible at low tide. Boy, it sure would suck to be trapped there overnight when the tide comes back in and there's a killer on the loose or something. (Look, I'm not telling you anything the book jacket doesn't already.) Among those at the party is our narrator, Daisy Darker, a girl with a suitcase full of unhappy family memories and a BIG secret. Don't worry if you forget that last part, Daisy will remind you. Frequently. So, this obvious homage to And Then There Were None is fine. The writing is a bit clunky in places (those hodge podge metered verses that were left as clues made my skin itch.) It's not deep or exceptional and you'll almost definitely guess the biggest mystery early on. (view spoiler)[Why do Daisy's family members ignore her every time she speaks and she never seems to have direct interactions with any of them? Yep, you are on the right Sunset Boulevard.
